#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""sable-spawn-worker — manager-invoked worker spawn for the tmux warm-pane
topology (SABLE-bldh.3). Replaces the in-process Agent-tool dispatch.

Per bead, a manager (Optimus/Tarzan) calls this to:
  1. resolve the worker model from the bead's `model:` label (or --model
     override) — a FLAT DEFAULT, not a ladder (SABLE-mn1da): no bead content is
     inspected to infer difficulty, and the choice + its source is announced on
     every spawn, default path included,
  2. (re)use a worktree (--worktree) or create one (`bd worktree create wk-<name>`),
  3. write the full dispatch prompt to a dispatch file (keeps the worktree clean),
  4. open a new tmux WINDOW running `claude --model <model>` with CWD = the worktree,
  5. tag the worker pane (@sable_role=worker / @sable_bead / @sable_status=running
     / @sable_lane=<owning manager>, SABLE-dcw2),
  6. send a single-line "read your dispatch file and execute it" instruction,
  7. stamp `model` / `model_source` metadata on the bead (and every --bundle
     sibling) from the command that ACTUALLY LAUNCHED — the durable answer to
     "which model ran this bead?" that no part of the record used to carry
     (SABLE-qw9jv). Written only after the pane exists, so a refused spawn
     leaves no attribution and a re-dispatch at another tier records the tier
     that ran.

The worker then runs the warm-pane self-push lifecycle (worker-dispatch.md):
self-push its branch and bd close. The done-flag itself is DETERMINISTIC
(SABLE-5v9n), not the worker's own discretionary final act: the spawned pane
command is wrapped (with_lifecycle_flags) so `tmux set-option -p -t
"$TMUX_PANE" @sable_status` flips running -> done from INSIDE the pane's own
script, unconditionally, when the worker's process exits — regardless of
whether the worker itself remembers to run it. The dispatch
prompt still also tells the worker to flag done as a belt-and-suspenders act
with an EXPLICIT target (omitting `-t` resolves the target from the
operator's active pane, not the worker's own — market-brief-package-uj22);
harmless if both fire, since the tmux command is idempotent. A worker that
treats `bd close` as the end of its job (the observed SABLE-2cao.1 failure,
where the LLM never ran the tmux command itself) no longer leaves its pane
stuck at `running` forever. `remain-on-exit` is also set globally (before the
window is created, so every pane inherits it from the start with no
post-creation race) so an exited pane survives long enough for
`sable-worker-status --reap` to observe the done tag and kill it, instead of
tmux silently destroying it the instant the wrapped command finishes.
Results flow back via the bead pool; `sable-worker-status --reap` cleans up.

Governance runs before the spawn unless --skip-governance: model-check + claim
(SABLE-bldh.6), plus duplicate-dispatch / overlap-advisory / P0-preempt /
worktree-refresh (SABLE-bldh.8) — the full set of what used to be separate
PreToolUse:Agent hooks (hooks/multi-manager/pre-dispatch-{overlap,preempt,
refresh}.sh), now re-homed as pre-spawn steps here since those hooks only ever
fired on the (now-unused) Agent dispatch path.

Respawn (SABLE-3eax): the manager REVISE / push-only close-out pattern
re-spawns a worker into the SAME worktree to finish a bead's landing. --respawn
(requires --worktree) makes that a first-class flow rather than needing the
blunt --skip-governance: it reopens a CLOSED bead to in_progress (so the claim
never traceback-crashes), releases a stranded tree-claim whose holder no longer
has a live pane, and passes the duplicate-dispatch guard when no LIVE pane
carries the bead tag — while KEEPING model-check active.

Usage:
  sable-spawn-worker <bead-id> [--worktree PATH] [--model M|--model M:reason]
                     [--scope NAME] [--session NAME] [--skip-governance]
                     [--respawn] [--bundle id1,id2,...]

  --bundle (SABLE-q13h): sibling bead ids dispatched alongside <bead-id> into
    the SAME worktree/branch. Every bundled bead is claimed up front (same as
    the lead) and its full title/description is rendered into the dispatch
    prompt itself, under a "Bundle contract" section binding the worker to
    ALL listed beads regardless of claim state — replacing the prior prose
    convention (a bundle spec left in the lead bead's notes/description) that
    lost non-lead beads in 6+ documented dispatches.

Env:
  SABLE_TMUX_SOCKET    tmux socket (-L) for isolation/tests
  SABLE_TMUX_SESSION   target session to spawn the worker window into (default: sable)
  SABLE_WORKER_CMD     override the worker command (default: 'claude --model <model>')
  SABLE_DISPATCH_DIR   where dispatch prompt files are written
                       (default: ~/.claude/sable/dispatch)
  SABLE_MAX_WORKERS    dispatch throttle (SABLE-mmdt): max live worker panes in
                       the session (default 8; 0 pauses spawning; invalid keeps
                       the default). Refusal = exit 7, names cap + live count.
  SABLE_MAX_LOAD_PER_CORE  host-resource guard (SABLE-mmdt): refuse spawning
                       when 1-min load average / cpu cores >= this threshold
                       (default 2.0; <=0 disables). Refusal = exit 8.
  SABLE_DISPATCH_READY_TIMEOUT  seconds to wait for composer posture before
                       giving up (default 25; 0 skips the wait entirely). A
                       pane that never reaches composer posture (still
                       booting, or stuck on an unrecognized dialog/selector,
                       SABLE-m94k) is never typed into — refusal = exit 10,
                       naming the pane; the bead stays claimed for retry.

Overlap scheduling constraint (SABLE-jd5fj.6): a bead whose declared file
footprint (wip_claims metadata / '## File footprint' description section /
WIP-CLAIMS text) overlaps a DIFFERENT in-progress bead's footprint refuses the
spawn — exit 11, naming the overlapping bead(s) and files. Two outs: wait for
the overlapping bead to clear, or add an explicit 'Serialize-with: <bead-id>'
line (bead notes/description) naming it — the spawn then proceeds and both
beads' `serialize_with` metadata is tagged for Chuck's for-chuck handoff.
"""
from __future__ import annotations

import argparse
import json
import os
import re
import shutil
import subprocess
import sys
from pathlib import Path
from typing import NamedTuple

# Shared pane-readiness/dispatch helpers (SABLE-bldh.14). Resolve the lib next to
# THIS script even when invoked via a PATH symlink.
sys.path.insert(0, os.path.dirname(os.path.realpath(__file__)))
from sable_pane_lib import (  # noqa: E402
    SessionCollision, WORKER_CAP_DEFAULT, accept_startup_gate, capture_pane,
    dialog_posture, dispatch_landed, pane_ready, repo_root, resolve_session,
    wait_for_ready, worker_cap,
)
from sable_pane_lib import deliver_text as deliver_dispatch  # noqa: E402

DEFAULT_SESSION = "sable"
DEFAULT_MODEL = "sonnet"


def _sanitize(s: str) -> str:
    return re.sub(r"[^a-z0-9]+", "-", s.lower()).strip("-")


def worktree_name(bead_id: str, scope: str | None) -> str:
    """wk-<scope|bead>, idempotent: a scope/bead_id that already sanitizes to a
    wk- prefix (e.g. 'wk-claim-hook-sandbox') is NOT double-prefixed into
    wk-wk-claim-hook-sandbox (SABLE-v2k3)."""
    base = _sanitize(scope) if scope else _sanitize(bead_id)
    if base.startswith("wk-"):
        base = base[len("wk-"):]
    return f"wk-{base}"


def window_name(bead_id: str) -> str:
    return f"worker-{_sanitize(bead_id)}"


def resolve_worktree_path(toplevel: str, wt_name: str) -> str:
    """Absolute worktree path = SIBLING of the repo root (its parent dir), NOT
    inside the repo. The SAME value must be handed to `bd worktree create` and to
    tmux `-c`; computing those two separately is what dropped the worker in $HOME
    (SABLE-bldh.11). Sibling (not inside-repo) also keeps the main checkout clean,
    which Chuck's merge requires (SABLE-936y) — an inside-repo worktree pollutes
    the repo-root .gitignore / shows as untracked."""
    return str(Path(toplevel).parent / wt_name)


# --- fixture linking (SABLE-ji4h) -------------------------------------------
# A git worktree materialises TRACKED files only. Gitignored integration
# fixtures therefore exist ONLY in the primary checkout, so every worker
# worktree silently loses them: costing-comparison's 22 integration tests
# skipped in every worker tree, and pytest exits 0 on an all-skipped run, so no
# gate caught it. Workers reported integration tests "passing" on runs where
# nothing executed. Proven both directions: 24 passed with the directory
# symlinked in, 24 skipped in the identical tree without it.
#
# GENERIC BY CONSTRAINT: no repo's directory names appear here. A repo opts in
# via `git config --add sable.fixturePath <relpath>` (repeatable). Worktrees
# share the primary checkout's config, so one setting covers every future tree.
#
# SYMLINK rather than copy: the source is gitignored customer material. A link
# commits nothing, copies nothing, exposes no byte not already on the machine
# under the same user, and the ignore rules stay in force inside the worktree,
# so a worker cannot `git add` the linked files even deliberately.

FIXTURE_PATH_CONFIG_KEY = "sable.fixturePath"


def configured_fixture_paths(toplevel: str) -> list[str]:
    """Repo-relative fixture paths opted in via sable.fixturePath. Empty (never
    an error) when the key is unset — repos that need nothing pay nothing.

    SABLE-6sdpx: `git config --get-all` documents exit 1 SPECIFICALLY for "the
    section or key is invalid" (i.e. legitimately unset) — that is the one
    nonzero code meaning empty-by-design, exactly like pytest's exit 5. Every
    OTHER nonzero code (2 bad params, 3 malformed config file, 128 not-a-repo,
    ...) is a real failure git could not even evaluate the key for, and must
    not be silently folded into "unconfigured", or a repo that genuinely opted
    in via sable.fixturePath would silently run every worker without its
    fixtures with no signal anywhere."""
    try:
        cp = subprocess.run(
            ["git", "-C", toplevel, "config", "--get-all", FIXTURE_PATH_CONFIG_KEY],
            capture_output=True, text=True, check=False,
        )
    except OSError:
        return []
    if cp.returncode == 1:
        return []  # key/section not found — legitimately unconfigured
    if cp.returncode != 0:
        print(f"sable-spawn-worker: WARNING git config --get-all "
              f"{FIXTURE_PATH_CONFIG_KEY} failed (exit {cp.returncode}) — "
              f"treating as unconfigured, fixtures may be silently skipped: "
              f"{cp.stderr.strip() or cp.stdout.strip()}", file=sys.stderr)
        return []
    return [ln.strip() for ln in cp.stdout.splitlines() if ln.strip()]


def plan_fixture_links(toplevel: str, worktree: str, rels: list[str]) -> list[tuple]:
    """Pure planner: -> [(rel, action, src, dst)] with action one of
    link | skip-missing-source | skip-exists | skip-escapes-repo.

    Split from the doer so the decision logic is unit-testable without a real
    worktree, and so a dry run can be inspected. Ordering of checks matters:
    containment is validated BEFORE existence so a traversal attempt is
    reported as such rather than as a missing source."""
    top, wt = Path(toplevel).resolve(), Path(worktree).resolve()
    plan = []
    for rel in rels:
        src, dst = (top / rel), (wt / rel)
        try:
            inside = src.resolve().is_relative_to(top) and dst.resolve().is_relative_to(wt)
        except (OSError, ValueError):
            inside = False
        if not inside:
            plan.append((rel, "skip-escapes-repo", str(src), str(dst)))
        elif not src.exists():
            plan.append((rel, "skip-missing-source", str(src), str(dst)))
        elif dst.exists() or dst.is_symlink():
            plan.append((rel, "skip-exists", str(src), str(dst)))
        else:
            plan.append((rel, "link", str(src), str(dst)))
    return plan


def link_fixture_paths(toplevel: str, worktree: str) -> list[tuple]:
    """Materialise the plan. Never raises: a fixture-link failure must not take
    down a dispatch that would otherwise succeed — the worker then runs without
    fixtures, which is exactly today's behaviour, and the strict-fixture guard
    (costing-comparison-0cp) is what turns that into a loud failure rather than
    a silent skip. Returns the plan with failures recorded as link-failed."""
    results = []
    for rel, action, src, dst in plan_fixture_links(toplevel, worktree, configured_fixture_paths(toplevel)):
        if action != "link":
            results.append((rel, action, src, dst))
            continue
        try:
            Path(dst).parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
            os.symlink(src, dst)
            results.append((rel, "link", src, dst))
        except OSError as e:
            results.append((rel, f"link-failed: {e}", src, dst))
    return results


class ModelChoice(NamedTuple):
    """(model, reason, source) — `source` is WHY this model was chosen:
    'override' (--model), 'label' (bead `model:` label), or 'default'
    (DEFAULT_MODEL, because neither was given)."""
    model: str
    reason: str | None
    source: str


def resolve_model(labels: list[str], override: str | None) -> ModelChoice:
    """Return ModelChoice(model, reason, source). Override syntax: 'opus' or
    'opus:why'. Label 'model:<m>' is the next signal; otherwise DEFAULT_MODEL.

    SABLE-mn1da: this is a FLAT DEFAULT, not a ladder. Nothing here inspects
    the bead to infer difficulty — not type, not priority, not description
    size, not whether it carries an unresolved ruling. The 'model ladder' in
    SABLE.md 6.9 / the role cards is a MANAGER judgment expressed through
    --model or a `model:` label; a manager who dispatches without either gets
    a constant. That gap used to be invisible at dispatch (only the override
    path announced itself) and surfaced 30+ minutes later as a shallow result,
    so `source` exists to make the default path as loud as the override one —
    see model_announcement."""
    if override:
        model, _, reason = override.partition(":")
        return ModelChoice(model.strip(), (reason.strip() or None), "override")
    for lab in labels:
        if lab.startswith("model:"):
            return ModelChoice(lab.split(":", 1)[1].strip(), None, "label")
    return ModelChoice(DEFAULT_MODEL, None, "default")


def model_announcement(model: str, reason: str | None, source: str) -> str:
    """Operator-visible one-liner naming the model AND why it was chosen
    (SABLE-mn1da). The reasoned-override wording is BYTE-IDENTICAL to what this
    tool has always printed ('model opus, override: <reason>') — the fix adds
    no noise to the path that already worked; it makes the two SILENT paths
    (default, and a bare unreasoned override) say what they are."""
    if source == "override":
        return f"model {model}, override: {reason}" if reason else \
            f"model {model}, override: (no reason given)"
    if source == "label":
        return f"model {model}, from bead label model:{model}"
    return (f"model {model}, DEFAULT — no --model override and no model: label; "
            "sable-spawn-worker does NOT infer difficulty from the bead")


# `--model X` / `--model=X` as it appears in the command actually handed to
# tmux. Used for provenance (SABLE-qw9jv): what LAUNCHED, not what was asked for.
# The value stops at shell punctuation, not just whitespace: with_lifecycle_flags
# joins the worker command to the done-flag write with `;`, so a command whose
# LAST token is the model (a bare SABLE_WORKER_CMD='claude --model opus') yields
# 'opus;' under a plain \S+ — a wrong value written straight into the bead.
_MODEL_FLAG_RE = re.compile(r"--model[=\s]+([^\s;&|'\"]+)")


def launched_model(worker_cmd: str) -> str | None:
    """The model named by the command that actually launches in the pane, or
    None when that command names no model at all (SABLE-qw9jv).

    This reads the FINAL command string — after worker_command() has applied
    any SABLE_WORKER_CMD override and after with_lifecycle_flags() has wrapped
    it — precisely because the dispatcher's REQUEST and what the spawn RUNS can
    diverge: a full SABLE_WORKER_CMD override replaces the command verbatim, so
    it may pin a different model, or none. Recording the request instead of the
    launch is the exact intent-vs-execution error this bead exists to kill."""
    m = _MODEL_FLAG_RE.search(worker_cmd or "")
    return m.group(1) if m else None


def parse_bead(raw: str) -> dict:
    data = json.loads(raw)
    return data[0] if isinstance(data, list) else data


def bead_labels(bead: dict) -> list[str]:
    return bead.get("labels") or []


def label_model(labels: list[str]) -> str | None:
    for lab in labels:
        if lab.startswith("model:"):
            return lab.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
    return None


def model_check(labels: list[str], override: str | None) -> str | None:
    """Re-homed pre-dispatch-model-check (SABLE-bldh.6): block an override that
    silently disagrees with the bead's model: label. Returns an error string to
    block, or None to allow. No label or no override => allow."""
    lm = label_model(labels)
    if not override or not lm:
        return None
    om, _, reason = override.partition(":")
    if om.strip() != lm and not reason.strip():
        return (f"--model override '{om.strip()}' disagrees with bead label "
                f"'model:{lm}' and gives no reason. Use --model {om.strip()}:<reason> "
                f"to override deliberately.")
    return None


def parse_bead_list(raw: str) -> list[dict]:
    """Best-effort parse of a `bd ... --json` array response. Empty list on any
    malformed/non-array payload — governance below fails OPEN, never blocks a
    spawn because a `bd` query hiccuped."""
    try:
        data = json.loads(raw)
    except Exception:
        return []
    return data if isinstance(data, list) else []


# Tab-delimited @sable_bead + @sable_status dump for dispatch-evidence detection
# (SABLE-676c) — same delimiter rationale as _CAP_FORMAT (SABLE-exab: empty
# fields collapse under space-joining, shifting columns).
_BEAD_FORMAT = "#{@sable_bead}\t#{@sable_status}"


def bead_pane_tagged(listing: str, bead_id: str) -> bool:
    """True if a RUNNING pane in `listing` is tagged @sable_bead == bead_id —
    hard evidence a worker is already dispatched for this bead. `listing` is a
    `list-panes -F _BEAD_FORMAT` dump. Only a RUNNING pane counts: a done/stale
    pane (SABLE-qq6r) has released its worker, and when the bead is still
    in_progress the durable duplicate signal is the leftover worktree, not the
    reaped pane. A blank/transient status is likewise NOT evidence — being strict
    here is what stops a bare claim-then-hold claim from false-positiving. Panes
    duplicated across grouped sessions (SABLE-b574) are harmless: any match ->
    True."""
    for line in listing.splitlines():
        parts = line.split("\t")
        pane_bead = parts[0] if parts else ""
        status = parts[1] if len(parts) >= 2 else ""
        if pane_bead == bead_id and status == "running":
            return True
    return False


def prospective_worktree_path(bead_id: str, scope: str | None,
                              worktree_override: str | None, toplevel: str) -> str:
    """The DERIVED worktree path a FRESH dispatch would create for this bead
    (`bd worktree create wk-<scope|bead>`, sibling of the repo — SABLE-bldh.11).
    Empty when the caller passed an explicit --worktree (an intentional reuse /
    revision re-spawn, NOT a duplicate — worktree-evidence must not fire on it)
    or when the repo toplevel can't be resolved."""
    if worktree_override or not toplevel:
        return ""
    return resolve_worktree_path(toplevel, worktree_name(bead_id, scope))


def worktree_dispatch_exists(path: str) -> bool:
    """True if the derived worktree a fresh dispatch would create already exists
    on disk — evidence a prior dispatch already cut it. Empty path => no
    evidence."""
    return bool(path) and os.path.isdir(path)


def already_in_progress_check(bead: dict, pane_evidence: bool,
                              worktree_evidence: bool,
                              respawn: bool = False) -> str | None:
    """Refuse a SECOND spawn for a bead already IN_PROGRESS — but ONLY when
    DISPATCH EVIDENCE exists (SABLE-676c). Evidence is a running worker pane
    tagged with the bead id (`bead_pane_tagged`) or an existing derived worktree
    (`worktree_dispatch_exists`).

    A bare IN_PROGRESS claim with NEITHER is the manager claim-then-hold pattern:
    a manager claims a bead to mark lane ownership during a coordination hold,
    then spawns when the hold lifts (the documented claim-THEN-spawn protocol).
    The old check (re-homed pre-dispatch-overlap, SABLE-bldh.8) refused that first
    dispatch as a duplicate purely because the bead was in_progress with no worker
    anywhere — the SABLE-676c false positive that forced the racy
    `bd update --status=open` workaround. Racing a live worker (or a leftover
    worktree from a died/stalled one) is still a real duplicate-work/double-push
    hazard and stays blocked. Returns an error string to block, or None to allow.

    respawn=True is the SABLE-3eax REVISE / push-only close-out: the worktree is
    being DELIBERATELY reused, so worktree-evidence is EXPECTED and never a
    duplicate signal — only a LIVE worker pane still carrying the bead tag blocks
    (two workers racing the same push). The reused tree is reconciled separately
    by releasing any stranded tree-claim (release_stale_tree_claim), not by
    refusing the dispatch."""
    if bead.get("status") != "in_progress":
        return None
    if respawn:
        worktree_evidence = False
    if not (pane_evidence or worktree_evidence):
        return None
    assignee = bead.get("assignee") or "unassigned"
    signals = []
    if pane_evidence:
        signals.append("a running worker pane tagged with this bead")
    if worktree_evidence:
        signals.append("an existing worktree for this bead")
    return (f"{bead.get('id', '?')} is already IN_PROGRESS (assignee: {assignee}) "
            f"with dispatch evidence — {'; '.join(signals)} — refusing a second "
            "spawn for the same bead. If the prior worker died or stalled, "
            "close/reset its worktree first. (A bare claim with no worker pane and "
            "no worktree is the claim-then-hold pattern and is allowed.)")


def extract_wip_claims(text: str) -> set[str]:
    """File paths from `WIP-CLAIMS: a, b, c` lines in bead notes/description."""
    claims: set[str] = set()
    for m in re.finditer(r"WIP-CLAIMS:\s*([^\n]+)", text or ""):
        for p in m.group(1).split(","):
            p = p.strip()
            if p:
                claims.add(p)
    return claims


def extract_footprint_section(text: str) -> set[str]:
    """Files from a planner-authored '## File footprint' description section
    (SABLE-jd5fj.6: DECOMPOSITION-authored declared footprint — see this bead's
    own description for the format). Entries are comma-separated; a trailing
    parenthetical annotation (e.g. 'bin/sable-spawn-worker (constraint
    surfacing)') is stripped to the leading path token so extension-less
    scripts are captured — the WIP-CLAIMS/metadata sources below don't need an
    extension either, but the OLD generic-regex fallback in the hook-based
    claim writer did, which is exactly the gap this section format closes."""
    m = re.search(r"^##\s*File footprint\s*\n(.+?)(?=\n##\s|\Z)", text or "",
                  re.MULTILINE | re.DOTALL)
    if not m:
        return set()
    files: set[str] = set()
    for part in m.group(1).split(","):
        part = part.strip()
        if not part:
            continue
        files.add(part.split()[0])
    return files


def bead_claimed_files(bead: dict) -> set[str]:
    """Union of every declared-footprint source for `bead`: WIP-CLAIMS text
    lines (notes/description), the wip_claims metadata field (SABLE-szd
    dedicated column — pre-dispatch-claim.sh's write target), and a planner-
    authored '## File footprint' description section (SABLE-jd5fj.6)."""
    text = (bead.get("notes") or "") + "\n" + (bead.get("description") or "")
    claims = extract_wip_claims(text) | extract_footprint_section(bead.get("description") or "")
    metadata = bead.get("metadata", {}) or {}
    wip_claims = metadata.get("wip_claims", "") or ""
    claims |= {p.strip() for p in wip_claims.split(",") if p.strip()}
    return claims


def extract_serialize_with(text: str) -> set[str]:
    """Bead ids named in a `Serialize-with: <id>[, <id>...]` line — the
    explicit out (SABLE-jd5fj.6) that permits dispatch despite an overlapping
    declared footprint. See overlap_check."""
    ids: set[str] = set()
    for m in re.finditer(r"Serialize-with:\s*([^\n]+)", text or "", re.IGNORECASE):
        for tok in re.split(r"[,\s]+", m.group(1).strip()):
            if tok:
                ids.add(tok)
    return ids


def bead_serialize_with(bead: dict) -> set[str]:
    text = (bead.get("notes") or "") + "\n" + (bead.get("description") or "")
    return extract_serialize_with(text)


class OverlapVerdict(NamedTuple):
    """decision: 'none' (no overlap, nothing to do) | 'deny' (SCHEDULING
    CONSTRAINT — the spawn must be refused) | 'allow' (overlap permitted via a
    matching Serialize-with line; tagged_ids names the partner bead(s) to tag
    serialize_with on both sides)."""
    decision: str
    message: str = ""
    tagged_ids: tuple[str, ...] = ()


def overlap_check(bead_id: str, bead: dict, in_progress: list[dict]) -> OverlapVerdict:
    """SABLE-jd5fj.6: overlap flips from ADVISORY (re-homed pre-dispatch-overlap,
    SABLE-bldh.8) to a SCHEDULING CONSTRAINT. A declared footprint overlapping a
    DIFFERENT in-progress bead's footprint DENIES the dispatch. Two named outs:
    wait for the in-progress bead to clear, or name the overlapping bead(s) in
    an explicit 'Serialize-with: <bead-id>' line (bead notes/description) — that
    ALLOWS the dispatch, and the caller tags both beads' `serialize_with`
    metadata so Chuck's for-chuck handoff sequences the merges together. Naming
    an unrelated bead in Serialize-with does not launder an uncovered overlap:
    every overlap hit must be covered, or the whole dispatch still denies.
    Same-bead duplication is handled separately (blocking) by
    already_in_progress_check()."""
    my_files = bead_claimed_files(bead)
    if not my_files:
        return OverlapVerdict("none")
    hits: list[tuple[str, str, list[str]]] = []
    for other in in_progress:
        oid = other.get("id", "")
        if not oid or oid == bead_id:
            continue
        shared = my_files & bead_claimed_files(other)
        if shared:
            hits.append((oid, other.get("assignee") or "unassigned", sorted(shared)))
    if not hits:
        return OverlapVerdict("none")

    serialize_with = bead_serialize_with(bead)
    uncovered = [h for h in hits if h[0] not in serialize_with]
    if uncovered:
        lines = "\n".join(
            f"  - {oid} ({assignee}, in-progress): {', '.join(files)}"
            for oid, assignee, files in uncovered
        )
        return OverlapVerdict(
            "deny",
            "OVERLAP DETECTED — this dispatch shares declared footprint with "
            f"active in-progress work:\n{lines}\n\nSCHEDULING CONSTRAINT: "
            "dispatch denied. Wait for the overlapping bead to clear, or add "
            "an explicit 'Serialize-with: <bead-id>' line naming it to proceed "
            "— both merges will be tagged serialize-together for Chuck.",
        )
    tagged = tuple(sorted({h[0] for h in hits}))
    return OverlapVerdict(
        "allow",
        f"SERIALIZE-WITH ACCEPTED — overlap with {', '.join(tagged)} permitted; "
        "tagging serialize-together for Chuck's handoff.",
        tagged,
    )


def tag_serialize_with(bead_id: str, partner_id: str) -> None:
    """Append `partner_id` to `bead_id`'s serialize_with metadata (dedup,
    sorted csv) — mirrors the wip_claims append convention
    (edit-write-claim-reconciler.sh) so a later metadata write from elsewhere
    never clobbers it. Best-effort: swallows bd errors, matching the rest of
    this module's fail-open governance writes."""
    try:
        current = parse_bead(_run(["bd", "show", bead_id, "--json"])) \
            .get("metadata", {}).get("serialize_with", "") or ""
    except Exception:
        current = ""
    existing = {p.strip() for p in current.split(",") if p.strip()}
    existing.add(partner_id)
    new_value = ",".join(sorted(existing))
    subprocess.run(["bd", "update", bead_id, "--sandbox", "--set-metadata",
                    f"serialize_with={new_value}"], capture_output=True, text=True)


def tag_branch_metadata(bead_id: str, branch: str) -> None:
    """Record `branch` as STRUCTURED metadata on `bead_id` (SABLE-i5739): the
    reconciliation floor (bin/sable-reconcile-handoffs find_work_bead_status)
    resolves a branch to its work bead by an EXACT metadata key/value match,
    never prose, so this write is what makes that resolution possible at all
    for a branch whose bead text never happens to name it. A plain overwrite
    (not an append like tag_serialize_with) — a bead has exactly one branch
    per dispatch, and a --respawn into the SAME worktree/branch just re-sets
    the same value. Best-effort: swallows bd errors, matching the rest of
    this module's fail-open governance writes — a missed tag degrades
    resolution to the legacy prose fallback, it never blocks dispatch."""
    subprocess.run(["bd", "update", bead_id, "--sandbox", "--set-metadata",
                    f"branch={branch}"], capture_output=True, text=True)


def tag_model_metadata(bead_id: str, model: str, source: str) -> None:
    """Record which model ACTUALLY RAN this bead, as structured metadata
    (SABLE-qw9jv): `model=<m>` plus `model_source=<override|label|default|
    worker-cmd-override>`.

    Nothing in the bead record used to capture this. A dispatch's `model:`
    label, a manager note, a dispatch prompt line — all of them are INTENT, and
    this fleet's own rule is that an instruction written into a bead is never
    evidence it executed. So a shift's worth of haiku-vs-sonnet analysis was
    unanswerable from the moment it was asked, across eight beads with zero
    durable attributions. This write is the artefact: emitted by the spawn
    path, not typed by a manager, and only AFTER the pane actually launched —
    a spawn refused by the throttle/host-guard/composer-posture gate writes
    nothing, so a bead refused at one tier and re-dispatched at another shows
    the tier that RAN, not the one first attempted.

    A plain overwrite, like tag_branch_metadata: a re-dispatch supersedes the
    previous attempt (dolt history keeps the prior values for anyone
    reconstructing the whole sequence). Best-effort — swallows bd errors,
    matching every other governance write here; a missed stamp must never
    block a dispatch."""
    for kv in (f"model={model}", f"model_source={source}"):
        subprocess.run(["bd", "update", bead_id, "--sandbox", "--set-metadata", kv],
                       capture_output=True, text=True)


def bead_already_claimed_by_lane(bead: dict, lane: str) -> bool:
    """True when `bead`'s assignee IS the dispatching lane already — regardless
    of who set it (a prior self-claim, the lane's own claim-then-hold, or a
    manager REASSIGNMENT by a different actor, e.g. lincoln reassigning a bead
    to optimus — SABLE-m40k design note). Real `bd update --claim` is only
    idempotent against bd's OWN actor identity (--actor/BEADS_ACTOR/git
    user.name/$USER), which never equals a SABLE lane name, so calling it here
    unconditionally errors 'already claimed by <lane>' and aborts the whole
    spawn (SABLE-m40k — the residual SABLE-676c left behind: the GUARD lets the
    claim-then-hold bead's dispatch through, but the claim CALL right after it
    still blows up). Empty lane never matches — an unassigned/lane-less bead is
    not "already mine"."""
    return bool(lane) and bead.get("assignee") == lane


def preempt_check(lane: str, inbox: list[dict]) -> str | None:
    """Re-homed pre-dispatch-preempt (SABLE-bldh.8): block dispatch when a
    priority-0 coord bead sits in the lane's inbox (`for-<lane>`). Existing
    dispatched workers are unaffected — only the NEXT dispatch. Empty lane =>
    allow (no identity to gate on). Returns an error string to block, or None."""
    if not lane:
        return None
    p0 = [f"{b.get('id', '')}: {b.get('title', '')}" for b in inbox
          if b.get("priority") == 0 and b.get("id")]
    if not p0:
        return None
    return (f"PREEMPTION ({lane}): priority-0 coord bead(s) in the lane inbox "
            "blocking next dispatch:\n" + "\n".join(p0) +
            "\n\nResolve with bd close, or set aside with: bd update <id> --notes "
            "\"deferred: <reason>\" then bd defer <id>.")


# --- unmerged-blocker advisory (SABLE-d5iku) ---------------------------------
#
# `bd ready` releases a dependent the instant its blocker's STATUS becomes
# closed. What a BASE-PREMISE bead needs is the blocker's CODE present on the
# branch it forks from, and those two events are separated by the whole merge
# queue. Every `bd dep add` used for structural sequencing therefore carries a
# false-release window in which the graph says go and the tree says not yet —
# and the false release looks EXACTLY like a correct one.
#
# THIS IS THE CHECK SITE, and it is here for a reason that cost one review
# cycle: the surfacing first landed in hooks/multi-manager/pre-dispatch-claim.sh,
# which is registered PreToolUse with matcher `Agent`. Managers do not dispatch
# workers with the Agent tool — they call THIS program, which is a bash
# invocation, so the guard was structurally incapable of firing on the only
# path it exists to guard (the bead's own live instance, SABLE-78kxu released
# by a closed-but-unmerged SABLE-9boz4, was a sable-spawn-worker dispatch).
# The hook leg is kept as a secondary surface for Agent-tool producer spawns;
# this one is the primary. Do not move it back.
#
# ADVISORY AND FAIL-OPEN, never a deny. Merge state has genuine unresolvable
# cases (pruned branches, stale remote-tracking refs, beads carrying no branch
# at all), so a withhold would trade the false-go for a false-block — and the
# ruled severity criterion makes DENY conditional on reliably discriminating
# base-premise edges from ordinary deps, which nothing in the graph does today.
# Option (b), merge-aware readiness at the source, lives in bd core.

def resolve_dep_check_bin() -> str | None:
    """Locate bin/sable-dep-check: explicit override, then PATH (the installed
    spine bin), then this program's own sibling for a dev checkout whose bins
    are not installed. Absent everywhere => None, and the advisory is skipped
    silently — a missing tool must never cost a dispatch."""
    override = os.environ.get("SABLE_DEP_CHECK_BIN", "")
    if override:
        return override if os.access(override, os.X_OK) else None
    found = shutil.which("sable-dep-check")
    if found:
        return found
    sibling = Path(__file__).resolve().parent / "sable-dep-check"
    return str(sibling) if os.access(sibling, os.X_OK) else None


# sable-dep-check's EXIT_UNKNOWN (SABLE-wezu1). Mirrored as a literal rather
# than imported — this program has no import path to a sibling CLI script, and
# the value is part of that tool's documented exit-code contract, not an
# implementation detail liable to drift silently under it.
_DEP_CHECK_EXIT_UNKNOWN = 4


def _dep_check_could_not_assess(reason: str) -> str:
    """The report dep_merge_advisory emits when sable-dep-check could not run
    to completion and left no text of its own to relay (SABLE-wezu1) — a bd
    hiccup that hangs or errors the OUTER call, not the tool's own well-formed
    exit-4 report (which already carries text via render_unknown_block and is
    simply returned as-is). Distinct from both the clean-silent `None` and a
    real UNMERGED-BLOCKER WARNING, so a manager reading stderr cannot mistake
    "I could not check" for "I checked, and it's clean"."""
    return (f"UNMERGED-BLOCKER CHECK COULD NOT ASSESS (SABLE-wezu1): {reason}. "
            "Merge state of any blocker is UNKNOWN, not verified — the "
            "dispatch is NOT blocked by this, but verify containment by hand "
            "before dispatching anything sequenced behind another bead: "
            "git merge-base --is-ancestor <blocker-branch> <integration>.")


def dep_merge_advisory(bead_ids: list[str], repo: str) -> str | None:
    """Run the checker over the beads being dispatched and return its warning
    or could-not-assess text, or None only on the genuinely healthy path.

    `--format=hook` prints a block and NOTHING when clean, so for a run that
    completes, emptiness is read as "checked, clean" and any text — a WARNING
    or the tool's own COULD-NOT-ASSESS block — is relayed unchanged; the exit
    code is not needed to tell those apart, because the tool's exit-4 path
    always carries its own text (render_unknown_block).

    But the checker not completing at all is a SEPARATE could-not-assess door,
    and it used to collapse into the same `None` the healthy path returns
    (SABLE-wezu1): a bd hiccup that hangs the OUTER subprocess.run past
    `timeout`, or one that raises before any text is captured, left nothing to
    relay. Those legs now report explicitly instead of going silent. So does a
    process that DOES exit 4 but — contrary to the tool's contract — emits no
    text; this is defensive, not the expected shape of that exit code, and
    exists so a future regression in the tool's own reporting cannot silently
    re-open this hole from the other side.

    The fail-OPEN decision is unchanged either way: this function never blocks
    the dispatch, it only changes what the manager reads on stderr. Disable
    entirely with SABLE_DEP_MERGE_GUARD=0.

    Timeout is larger than the hook leg's (which must fit a 5s PreToolUse
    budget); here the only cost of waiting is dispatch latency, and the
    checker's floor is two `bd` invocations at ~0.8s of process startup each
    (SABLE-kqaj9). Tune with SABLE_DEP_CHECK_TIMEOUT."""
    if os.environ.get("SABLE_DEP_MERGE_GUARD", "1") != "1":
        return None
    ids = [b for b in bead_ids if b]
    if not ids:
        return None
    binary = resolve_dep_check_bin()
    if not binary:
        return None
    try:
        timeout = float(os.environ.get("SABLE_DEP_CHECK_TIMEOUT", "8"))
    except ValueError:
        timeout = 8.0
    try:
        proc = subprocess.run(
            [binary, "--format=hook", "--repo", repo, *ids],
            capture_output=True, text=True, timeout=timeout)
    except subprocess.TimeoutExpired:
        return _dep_check_could_not_assess(
            f"sable-dep-check did not finish within {timeout:g}s (bd likely "
            "contended/locked) — the check was killed before it could report")
    except (OSError, subprocess.SubprocessError) as exc:
        return _dep_check_could_not_assess(
            f"sable-dep-check failed to run — {exc}")
    out = (proc.stdout or "").strip()
    if out:
        return out
    if proc.returncode == _DEP_CHECK_EXIT_UNKNOWN:
        return _dep_check_could_not_assess(
            f"sable-dep-check exited {_DEP_CHECK_EXIT_UNKNOWN} (COULD NOT "
            "ASSESS) but produced no report text")
    return None


# --- dispatch throttle + host-resource guard (SABLE-mmdt) ---------------------
#
# 3 managers x ~15 concurrent worker panes + the Docker stack froze the WSL host
# (2026-07-07, hard shutdown; load ~46 on 14 cores re-confirmed it 2026-07-13).
# Nothing bounded spawn concurrency: managers dispatched every ready bead at
# once. These checks run BEFORE any bead mutation and are NOT gated by
# --skip-governance — they protect the HOST, not bead hygiene.

# Tab-delimited like sable-worker-status's _FORMAT (SABLE-exab: empty fields
# collapse under space-joining, shifting columns). #{window_name} (SABLE-6xtx)
# mirrors the same fallback field sable-worker-status's classifier added — this
# counter had the identical tag-only blindness (a pane whose
# @sable_role/@sable_class tags are absent/lost was invisible here too). A
# live-process-based (#{pane_current_command}) done override was ALSO tried
# here and reverted: this project's integration-test fixtures simulate a
# "running" worker with a plain `bash --noprofile --norc` pane and never
# launch a real claude process, so the live foreground command is indistinguishable
# from "claude exited" by that heuristic — see sable-worker-status's
# WINDOW_NAME_WORKER_PREFIX comment for the full incident.
_CAP_FORMAT = "#{@sable_role}\t#{@sable_status}\t#{@sable_class}\t#{window_name}"

# SABLE-6xtx: sable-spawn-worker's own window_name() always stamps this prefix
# at creation, independent of the @sable_role/@sable_class pane options — the
# same fallback classification signal sable-worker-status uses.
_WINDOW_NAME_WORKER_PREFIX = "worker-"


def count_live_workers(listing: str) -> int:
    """Live worker panes in a `list-panes -F _CAP_FORMAT` listing: class-stamped
    workers plus legacy classless panes whose role starts with 'worker' OR
    whose window name carries the worker-<bead> prefix (SABLE-6xtx fallback —
    the same recognition rule as sable-worker-status), excluding done panes — a
    done-but-unreaped worker has released its claude process and must not hold
    a dispatch slot. Managers and bounded producers never count. An EMPTY
    status counts as live: a just-spawned pane may not carry its tag yet."""
    n = 0
    for line in listing.splitlines():
        parts = line.split("\t")
        role = parts[0] if parts else ""
        status = parts[1] if len(parts) >= 2 else ""
        cls = parts[2] if len(parts) >= 3 else ""
        window = parts[3] if len(parts) >= 4 else ""
        is_worker = cls == "worker" or (
            not cls and (role.startswith("worker") or window.startswith(_WINDOW_NAME_WORKER_PREFIX)))
        if is_worker and status != "done":
            n += 1
    return n


def capacity_check(live: int, cap: int) -> str | None:
    """Refuse a spawn at/over the cap. The message names BOTH the cap and the
    live count — operator observability is part of the SABLE-mmdt acceptance.
    Returns an error string to block, or None to allow."""
    if live < cap:
        return None
    return (f"{live} live worker pane(s) >= cap {cap} (SABLE_MAX_WORKERS, "
            f"default {WORKER_CAP_DEFAULT}). One-in-one-out: respawn after a "
            "worker flips done (`sable-worker-status --reap` frees slots; "
            "`sable-view` shows live count vs cap). Raise the cap only "
            "deliberately — the 2026-07-07 full-fleet dispatch froze the host.")


LOAD_PER_CORE_DEFAULT = 2.0


def load_threshold() -> float:
    """SABLE_MAX_LOAD_PER_CORE (default 2.0; unparseable keeps the default,
    <=0 disables the guard — see host_guard)."""
    raw = (os.environ.get("SABLE_MAX_LOAD_PER_CORE") or "").strip()
    if not raw:
        return LOAD_PER_CORE_DEFAULT
    try:
        return float(raw)
    except ValueError:
        return LOAD_PER_CORE_DEFAULT


def host_guard(load1: float, cores: int, threshold: float) -> str | None:
    """Refuse to ADD a worker when the host is already saturated: 1-min load
    average per core at/over `threshold`. A non-positive threshold disables the
    guard. Returns an error string to block, or None to allow."""
    if threshold <= 0:
        return None
    cores = max(cores or 1, 1)
    per_core = load1 / cores
    if per_core < threshold:
        return None
    return (f"host overloaded — 1-min load {load1:.1f} on {cores} core(s) = "
            f"{per_core:.2f}/core, >= threshold {threshold:.2f} "
            "(SABLE_MAX_LOAD_PER_CORE). Refusing to add a worker; retry when "
            "load drops.")


def _ref_exists(worktree: str, ref: str) -> bool:
    return subprocess.run(
        ["git", "-C", worktree, "rev-parse", "--verify", "--quiet", ref],
        capture_output=True).returncode == 0


def resolve_base_ref(worktree: str, desired: str) -> str:
    """Mirrors lib-identity.sh's sable_validate_base_ref: if `desired` doesn't
    exist in `worktree`, fall back to origin/main, then @{upstream}, so a stale
    SABLE_BASE_BRANCH never hard-fails the refresh below (SABLE-61n)."""
    if _ref_exists(worktree, desired):
        return desired
    if desired != "origin/main" and _ref_exists(worktree, "origin/main"):
        return "origin/main"
    up = subprocess.run(
        ["git", "-C", worktree, "rev-parse", "--abbrev-ref", "--symbolic-full-name",
         "@{upstream}"], capture_output=True, text=True)
    if up.returncode == 0 and up.stdout.strip():
        return up.stdout.strip()
    return desired


def resolve_integration_branch(repo_path: str) -> str:
    """Python mirror of lib-identity.sh's sable_resolve_integration_branch
    (market-brief-package-2u25 / SABLE-ybdm): the BARE name of `repo_path`'s OWN
    integration branch. Integration-branch identity is a property of the TARGET
    REPO, not the session that happens to spawn into it — a session's
    $SABLE_BASE_BRANCH is configured once per project and leaks unchanged into
    every other repo that session touches. Consulted in order, first match wins:
      1. `git -C <repo> config --get sable.integrationBranch` (repo-local, unshared)
      2. `<repo>/.sable` file, a line `integrationBranch=<name>` (checked in, shared)
      3. $SABLE_INTEGRATION_BRANCH (explicit env override, bare name)
      4. $SABLE_BASE_BRANCH with a leading `origin/` stripped
      5. "main"
    Always returns a bare branch name."""
    if repo_path:
        cfg = subprocess.run(
            ["git", "-C", repo_path, "config", "--get", "sable.integrationBranch"],
            capture_output=True, text=True)
        val = cfg.stdout.strip() if cfg.returncode == 0 else ""
        if val:
            return val
        sable_file = Path(repo_path) / ".sable"
        if sable_file.is_file():
            for line in sable_file.read_text().splitlines():
                if line.startswith("integrationBranch="):
                    val = line[len("integrationBranch="):].strip()
                    if val:
                        return val
    val = (os.environ.get("SABLE_INTEGRATION_BRANCH")
           or os.environ.get("SABLE_BASE_BRANCH") or "origin/main")
    return val[len("origin/"):] if val.startswith("origin/") else val


def resolve_refresh_base(worktree: str, base_branch: str | None) -> str:
    """Resolve the ref refresh_worktree rebases a reused worktree onto. Ports the
    SABLE-4amz shape from pre-push-rebase-test.sh: the base DEFAULTS to this
    repo's OWN published integration branch (origin/<INT>) rather than an
    unconditional origin/main — the old default silently re-parented a reused
    worker branch on a non-main integration repo (tmux-only here) onto DIVERGED
    origin/main lineage at spawn time (SABLE-ybdm). An explicit base_branch
    (SABLE_BASE_BRANCH) still wins; validation falls back gracefully when the
    chosen ref doesn't exist (SABLE-61n). Assumes refs are already fetched, so
    the origin/<INT> existence check sees fresh remote refs."""
    integration = resolve_integration_branch(worktree)
    default_base = "origin/main"
    if integration and _ref_exists(worktree, f"origin/{integration}"):
        default_base = f"origin/{integration}"
    return resolve_base_ref(worktree, base_branch or default_base)


def refresh_worktree(worktree: str, base_branch: str | None) -> str | None:
    """Re-homed pre-dispatch-refresh (SABLE-bldh.8) — lowest priority per the
    bead: only relevant when REUSING an existing worktree via --worktree, since
    a freshly `bd worktree create`d tree is already at the base HEAD, and the
    worker itself rebases again before its final commit (worker-dispatch.md).
    Non-blocking: on fetch/rebase failure, aborts the half-done rebase and
    returns a warning instead of failing the spawn.

    Stands down (warns, no fetch/rebase) rather than operating on a fallback in
    two cases ported from wip-hook-fixes-d038, SABLE-4byx:
      * invalid/missing worktree path — never rebase a fallback (e.g. cwd);
      * primary-checkout target — a linked worktree has git-dir != git-common-dir;
        the PRIMARY checkout resolves them identically. Rebasing the shared main
        tree races concurrent dispatches and rewrites the session branch
        (market-brief-package-o45j)."""
    # --- SABLE-4byx: invalid/missing worktree path — refuse a fallback.
    if not worktree or not os.path.isdir(worktree):
        return (f"refresh: no valid worktree path ({worktree!r}); standing down "
                "(no fetch/rebase). Name an absolute existing worktree to refresh.")
    # --- SABLE-4byx: primary-checkout guard (market-brief-package-o45j). Only a
    # LINKED worktree is a refresh target, never the primary checkout — even when
    # named explicitly. In a linked worktree git-dir differs from git-common-dir;
    # in the primary checkout they resolve identically. Fail-safe: if resolution
    # fails (empty git-dir), stand down.
    git_dir = subprocess.run(
        ["git", "-C", worktree, "rev-parse", "--absolute-git-dir"],
        capture_output=True, text=True)
    common_dir = subprocess.run(
        ["git", "-C", worktree, "rev-parse", "--path-format=absolute",
         "--git-common-dir"], capture_output=True, text=True)
    gd = git_dir.stdout.strip() if git_dir.returncode == 0 else ""
    cd = common_dir.stdout.strip() if common_dir.returncode == 0 else ""
    if not gd or gd == cd:
        return (f"refresh: {worktree} is the primary checkout (git-dir == "
                "git-common-dir), not a linked worktree; standing down (no "
                "fetch/rebase) to avoid the shared-tree rebase race (o45j).")

    fetch = subprocess.run(["git", "-C", worktree, "fetch", "origin"],
                           capture_output=True, text=True)
    if fetch.returncode != 0:
        return f"refresh: fetch failed for {worktree}: {fetch.stderr.strip()[:300]}"
    # SABLE-ybdm: resolve the base AFTER the fetch so the origin/<INT> existence
    # check sees fresh remote refs (mirrors the 4amz post-fetch resolution).
    base = resolve_refresh_base(worktree, base_branch)
    rebase = subprocess.run(["git", "-C", worktree, "rebase", base],
                            capture_output=True, text=True)
    if rebase.returncode != 0:
        subprocess.run(["git", "-C", worktree, "rebase", "--abort"],
                       capture_output=True, text=True)
        return (f"refresh: rebase of {worktree} on {base} failed and was aborted: "
                f"{(rebase.stdout + rebase.stderr).strip()[:300]}")
    return None


# --- respawn (REVISE / push-only close-out) support (SABLE-3eax) --------------


def needs_reopen(bead: dict) -> bool:
    """(a) SABLE-3eax: a respawn targets a bead that was CLOSED (its landing is
    being finished / revised). It must be reopened to in_progress BEFORE the
    claim/close flow, or the unconditional `bd update --claim` traceback-crashes
    (a closed bead is not claimable — the actual blocker observed 2026-07-14)."""
    return bead.get("status") == "closed"


def tree_claim_file(worktree: str) -> str | None:
    """The tree-claim lockfile path for `worktree`, or None outside a git repo.
    Mirrors tree-claim.sh / sable-claim: `$(git -C <wt> rev-parse --git-dir)`
    then `/sable-tree-claim`. For a LINKED worktree the git-dir is the
    per-worktree `.git/worktrees/<name>`, so each worktree has its OWN claim file
    (a relative git-dir on older git is resolved against the worktree)."""
    r = subprocess.run(["git", "-C", worktree, "rev-parse", "--git-dir"],
                       capture_output=True, text=True)
    gd = r.stdout.strip() if r.returncode == 0 else ""
    if not gd:
        return None
    if not os.path.isabs(gd):
        gd = os.path.join(worktree, gd)
    return os.path.join(gd, "sable-tree-claim")


def release_stale_tree_claim(worktree: str, holder_pane_live: bool) -> str | None:
    """(b) SABLE-3eax: a reaped worker session strands its worktree tree-claim
    (`<worktree-gitdir>/sable-tree-claim`); until it TTL-expires (default 3600s),
    tree-claim.sh DENIES the respawned worker's index-mutating git ops, so the
    spawn was blocked until a manual `sable-claim release --force`. When
    respawning into a worktree whose claim holder no longer has a live pane,
    release the claim so the fresh worker isn't blocked.

    holder_pane_live is the liveness signal: a worktree's tree-claim is, by
    construction, held by the worker session working IN that worktree, and that
    worker's pane is the bead-tagged pane — so "no live pane carries the bead
    tag" (holder_pane_live=False) means the holder session is gone. A LIVE holder
    is never disturbed (and a live pane also refuses the respawn upstream via the
    duplicate guard). No-op when there is no claim file or the path is not a git
    repo. Returns a status message when it releases, else None."""
    if holder_pane_live:
        return None
    cf = tree_claim_file(worktree)
    if not cf or not os.path.isfile(cf):
        return None
    try:
        os.remove(cf)
    except OSError as e:
        return f"respawn: could not release stale tree-claim {cf}: {e}"
    return (f"respawn: released stale tree-claim {cf} (holder session has no live "
            "pane) so the fresh worker's git ops are not denied until TTL")


def worker_command(model: str, override: str | None) -> str:
    """Default worker command pins the model AND an auto-approving permission
    posture — a hands-off worker must run writes AND bash (mkdir/pytest/git/tmux)
    without prompting (SABLE-bldh.12). Tune via SABLE_WORKER_PERMISSION; a full
    SABLE_WORKER_CMD override (e.g. tests) replaces everything verbatim."""
    if override:
        return override
    perm = os.environ.get("SABLE_WORKER_PERMISSION", "--permission-mode bypassPermissions")
    return f"claude --model {model} {perm}".strip()


def with_lifecycle_flags(cmd: str) -> str:
    """Wrap `cmd` so its OWN pane process flips @sable_status running -> done
    itself, at both ends (SABLE-5v9n). `running` is set as the FIRST action,
    before `cmd` starts; `done` is set LAST, unconditionally, once `cmd` exits
    — `;` (not `&&`) is deliberate: the flag must flip even when `cmd` exits
    non-zero or crashes, since whether the worker succeeded is irrelevant to
    whether the pane is DONE running.

    Both flips happen INSIDE the pane's own shell, sequentially in the SAME
    script as `cmd` — the manager does NOT separately set @sable_status via
    its own post-creation `set-option` call (see main(): only @sable_role/
    @sable_bead/@sable_repo are set that way). A manager-side 'running' write
    races a fast-exiting worker (a test stand-in, or a `claude` boot that
    dies immediately): if the worker's own done-flip lands before the
    manager's post-creation call fires, that call CLOBBERS done back to
    running — observed while writing this fix's own integration test, whose
    stub worker exits in milliseconds. Doing both flips from inside the pane
    removes the two-actor race entirely: @sable_status is written by exactly
    one process, in one deterministic order, regardless of how fast `cmd`
    runs. $TMUX_PANE is set by tmux for any process running inside a pane
    from the moment it starts, so no pane id needs to be known up front and
    no readiness wait is needed before the leading `running` write.

    Previously the done-flag was the worker LLM's own DISCRETIONARY final
    act — a worker that treated `bd close` as the end of its job (the
    observed SABLE-2cao.1 failure) left its pane stuck at `running` forever,
    so `sable-worker-status --reap` never reclaimed it. Applied to the
    resolved command AFTER any SABLE_WORKER_CMD override, deliberately: the
    wrapping must be unconditional across every worker command shape,
    including test stand-ins, not just the default `claude` invocation."""
    tag = 'tmux set-option -p -t "$TMUX_PANE" @sable_status'
    return f'{tag} running; {cmd}; {tag} done'


def resolve_lane(override: str | None) -> str:
    """The identity to stamp on the worker = the invoking LANE MANAGER. Explicit
    --lane wins; else this process's CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME (the manager pane that ran
    sable-spawn-worker); else empty. The worker must carry a MANAGER identity
    because post-push-merge-notify (which files the for-chuck handoff) fires only
    for managers (SABLE-bldh.13)."""
    if override:
        return override.strip()
    return (os.environ.get("CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME") or "").strip()


def worker_pane_tags(bid: str, root: str, lane: str) -> list[tuple[str, str]]:
    """The per-pane @options sable-spawn-worker stamps POST-creation. NOT
    @sable_status — with_lifecycle_flags owns that from inside the pane's own
    script (SABLE-5v9n), so a manager-side write here would race a fast-exiting
    worker's done-flip. @sable_repo (SABLE-e1e3.2) and @sable_lane (SABLE-dcw2)
    are each stamped ONLY when resolvable — matching how an unset value renders
    as an absent tag rather than an empty one, so a downstream consumer can tell
    "no value" from "empty value".

    @sable_lane is the OWNING manager (== the resolved lane). Without it a
    worker carried its lane only in ENV (CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME via tmux -e),
    invisible to sable-worker-status, so any manager's sweep saw — and --reap'd
    — every manager's panes: a sweep adopted another lane's just-spawned workers
    as orphans, and a reap consumed DONE panes the owning manager was still
    event-waiting on. As a pane @option it drives that tool's own-lane default
    filter (filter_by_lane)."""
    tags = [("@sable_role", "worker"), ("@sable_bead", bid)]
    if root:
        tags.append(("@sable_repo", root))
    if lane:
        tags.append(("@sable_lane", lane))
    return tags


def worker_env_args(lane: str) -> list[str]:
    """tmux `-e` args for the worker pane.

    Two purposes, deliberately separated:
      * Lane identity (CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME=<lane> + manager role): stamped so the
        worker's push fires the manager-gated for-chuck handoff attributed to the
        lane, not the session-default lincoln (SABLE-bldh.13). Without it the
        worker inherits the tmux SESSION env (CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME=lincoln, set by
        sable-tmux's `new-session -e`). Omitted when no lane is resolvable.
      * SABLE_WORKER_PANE=1 (ALWAYS stamped): marks the pane as a WORKER. That
        manager identity is exactly what let a worker BOOT as its manager and
        re-dispatch its own bead (SABLE-38zi: identity bleed -> the SessionStart
        role-anchor loaded the tarzan role-card, the pane ran the manager loop
        and spawned a SECOND worker for the same bead, defeating the
        SABLE_MAX_WORKERS cap). This marker is the disambiguator: the role-anchor
        stands down on it (never loads a manager role-card into a worker), and
        sable-spawn-worker itself refuses to re-dispatch from a pane carrying it
        (worker_pane_guard). It is independent of lane so even a lane-less worker
        pane is recognizable."""
    args: list[str] = []
    if lane:
        args += ["-e", f"CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME={lane}", "-e", "CLAUDE_AGENT_ROLE=manager"]
    args += ["-e", "SABLE_WORKER_PANE=1"]
    return args


def worker_pane_guard() -> str | None:
    """SABLE-38zi hard guard: refuse to dispatch a worker FROM a worker pane.

    A worker pane carries SABLE_WORKER_PANE=1 (worker_env_args), inherited by any
    command it runs. A worker's job is to execute its ONE dispatched bead and
    self-push; it never spawns workers. If a worker ever (mis)invokes
    sable-spawn-worker — the observed failure was a worker that booted as its lane
    MANAGER via identity bleed and re-dispatched its own bead — this guard stops
    it dead, so one dispatch can never silently become two live panes / two
    worktrees and defeat the SABLE_MAX_WORKERS host-oversubscription cap.
    Returns an error string to block, or None to allow (not a worker pane)."""
    if not os.environ.get("SABLE_WORKER_PANE"):
        return None
    return ("refusing to dispatch from a WORKER pane (SABLE_WORKER_PANE set). A "
            "worker runs its single dispatched bead and self-pushes; it never "
            "spawns workers. This guard stops the SABLE-38zi re-dispatch — one "
            "dispatch silently becoming two live panes/worktrees, defeating the "
            "SABLE_MAX_WORKERS cap. If you are a MANAGER, dispatch from your own "
            "manager pane, not from inside a worker's.")


def claim_bundle_beads(bundle: list[dict], lane: str) -> None:
    """Claim-all-up-front (SABLE-q13h DESIGN, third leg alongside prompt
    injection + the done-flag gate): claim every bundled sibling bead the same
    way the lead bead is claimed, so none of them LOOKS separately-owned to
    the dispatched worker — directly closing the 7a6h+np7c failure mechanism
    (a worker declined a bundled bead because a manager's pre-claim made it
    look like someone else's work). Non-fatal: a claim failure on a sibling is
    warned to stderr, not raised — the in-prompt bundle contract is the
    primary mechanism (assemble_dispatch_prompt), this is belt-and-suspenders,
    and a sibling that's already claimed by someone else must not abort the
    whole dispatch of the lead bead."""
    for b in bundle:
        if bead_already_claimed_by_lane(b, lane):
            continue
        r = subprocess.run(["bd", "update", b.get("id", ""), "--claim"],
                           capture_output=True, text=True)
        if r.returncode != 0:
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-spawn-worker: could not claim bundled bead "
                f"{b.get('id', '?')}: {r.stderr.strip()}\n")


def new_window_args(session: str, win: str, worktree: str,
                    env_args: list[str], wcmd: str) -> list[str]:
    """tmux argv for the worker window. -d spawns it in the BACKGROUND: without
    it tmux makes each fresh worker window the session's current window, yanking
    every attached client's view on every dispatch (SABLE-zgbt). Delivery is
    unaffected — the -P -F pane-id capture works for detached windows, and
    wait_for_ready / send-keys target that pane id, never the current window."""
    return ["new-window", "-d", "-t", session, "-n", win, "-c", worktree,
            *env_args, "-P", "-F", "#{pane_id}", wcmd]


# pane_ready / accept_startup_gate / dialog_posture / dispatch_landed /
# wait_for_ready / deliver_dispatch (= deliver_text) / capture_pane now live in
# sable_pane_lib (imported above), shared with sable-tmux --autostart
# (SABLE-bldh.14) and, for dialog_posture, the fleet-wide liveness probe
# (SABLE-axp0).


def parse_bundle_ids(raw: str | None, lead_id: str) -> list[str]:
    """Parse `--bundle "id1, id2"` into a deduped, order-preserving list of
    sibling bead ids (SABLE-q13h). Blank entries and the lead id itself
    (listing the lead again in --bundle is a no-op, not an error) are
    dropped. None/empty `raw` => no bundle."""
    if not raw:
        return []
    seen: set[str] = set()
    out: list[str] = []
    for tok in raw.split(","):
        tok = tok.strip()
        if not tok or tok == lead_id or tok in seen:
            continue
        seen.add(tok)
        out.append(tok)
    return out


def bundle_ready_for_done(bundle_ids: list[str], bead_statuses: dict[str, str]) -> str | None:
    """The done-flag gate for a bundled dispatch (SABLE-q13h): returns None
    when every id in `bundle_ids` is closed per `bead_statuses`, else an error
    string naming the still-open sibling(s). A worker (or a manager auditing a
    'done' pane) uses this to refuse flagging done while a bundled bead
    remains open — the recurring failure mode this bead documents is the lead
    bead's own completion silently ending the worker's turn while siblings sit
    untouched. `bead_statuses` maps bead id -> its `bd show --json` status
    string; a bead absent from the map is treated as not-closed (fail safe,
    not fail open — an unknown status must not pass the gate)."""
    open_ids = [b for b in bundle_ids if bead_statuses.get(b) != "closed"]
    if not open_ids:
        return None
    return (f"bundle incomplete — still open: {', '.join(open_ids)}. Do not flag "
            "done until every bundled bead is closed or explicitly handed back "
            "(bd q \"<one-liner>\" explaining why).")


def assemble_dispatch_prompt(bead_id, title, description, worktree, branch, model,
                             bundle: list[dict] | None = None) -> str:
    """`bundle` (SABLE-q13h), when non-empty, is a list of {id, title,
    description} dicts for sibling beads dispatched alongside `bead_id` in the
    SAME worktree/branch. Every bundled bead's FULL description is rendered
    inline here — not left for the worker to go find in a lead bead's notes
    (the fybj+vyhn failure: a worker never read past the dispatch prompt into
    notes where a bundle addendum lived) — and the bundle contract below binds
    the worker to every listed bead regardless of claim state (the 7a6h+np7c
    failure: a worker declined a bundled bead because a manager pre-claim made
    it look separately-owned)."""
    bundle = bundle or []
    all_ids = [bead_id] + [b["id"] for b in bundle]

    bundled_sections = "".join(
        f"\n## Bundled bead — {b['id']}: {b['title']}\n\n{b['description']}\n"
        for b in bundle
    )

    bundle_contract = ""
    if bundle:
        ids_line = ", ".join(all_ids)
        status_checks = "\n".join(f"  bd show {i} --json" for i in all_ids)
        bundle_contract = f"""
## Bundle contract (SABLE-q13h) — READ THIS
This dispatch bundles {len(all_ids)} beads into ONE worktree/branch: {ids_line}.
ALL of them are yours to finish, regardless of who claimed what or whether a
bundled bead looks separately-owned — a pre-claim on a bundled bead does NOT
mean it isn't yours. The lead bead ({bead_id}) closing is NOT the end of your
task while any bundled sibling remains open. Before flagging done, verify
every bead in the bundle is closed:
{status_checks}
If any bead is not closed, finish it or hand it back explicitly with
`bd q "<one-liner>"` before flagging done — do not flag done with a bundled
bead still open.
"""

    close_line = (f"`bd close {bead_id}` and every other bundled bead listed above"
                 if bundle else f"`bd close {bead_id}`")
    verify_line = (f"`bd show <id> --json` for {ids_line if bundle else ''}"
                  if bundle else f"`bd show {bead_id} --json`")

    return f"""# SABLE worker dispatch — warm-pane self-push

You are a SABLE worker. You are a warm `claude` session in your own tmux pane,
and your shell CWD already IS your worktree. Follow the warm-pane self-push
contract below.

Worktree: {worktree}
Branch: {branch}
Worker model: {model}

## Bead
{bead_id}: {title}

{description}
{bundled_sections}{bundle_contract}
## Contract
- Verify current state first; if the work is already done / clean, STOP and report.
- Implement, then run the UNIT and INTEGRATION tests; capture the exact command + output.
- Rebase on the base branch, commit, and push YOUR OWN branch with plain
  `git push` from this CWD. NEVER use `git -C <other-tree>` — your CWD is the
  worktree (this deletes the SABLE-041 wrong-tree bug). Do NOT bypass pre-push.
- The post-push hook files the for-chuck handoff; Chuck merges. You do NOT open PRs.
- {close_line} with the test evidence. Check the exit code for each close —
  a non-zero exit (e.g. the TDD gate denying the close) means it did NOT
  close. Do not report success on a failed close; read the gate's stderr
  reason, fix the real cause (missing test evidence, or add [no-test] to
  the bead's notes if it is genuinely non-code), and retry.
- Verify every close actually landed: {verify_line} and confirm each
  `status` is `closed` BEFORE reporting success or flagging done
  (SABLE-u0c6 — claiming "closed" without this check is how a denied close
  gets mis-reported as success, stranding the bead in_progress with a
  pushed branch).
- Finally, flag done for the reaper. First verify your own pane identity
  (`echo $TMUX_PANE`), then target it explicitly — do NOT omit `-t`, or the
  flag lands on whichever pane has operator focus instead of your own:
  `tmux set-option -p -t "$TMUX_PANE" @sable_status done`.
"""


def read_instruction(dispatch_path: str) -> str:
    return (f"Read {dispatch_path} in full and execute the SABLE worker dispatch "
            f"it contains. It is your complete task.")


def dispatch_dir() -> Path:
    return Path(os.environ.get("SABLE_DISPATCH_DIR")
                or (Path.home() / ".claude" / "sable" / "dispatch"))


def tmux_base(socket: str | None) -> list[str]:
    return ["tmux", "-L", socket] if socket else ["tmux"]


def _run(args: list[str]) -> str:
    return subprocess.run(args, capture_output=True, text=True, check=True).stdout


def _repo_toplevel() -> str:
    """The invoking CWD's git worktree root, or "" if not resolvable — used to
    derive the prospective wk-<scope> worktree path for dispatch-evidence
    detection (SABLE-676c). Non-raising, unlike _run: absence of a toplevel just
    means no worktree-evidence."""
    r = subprocess.run(["git", "rev-parse", "--show-toplevel"],
                       capture_output=True, text=True)
    return r.stdout.strip() if r.returncode == 0 else ""


def _live_bead_pane(base: list[str], session: str, bead_id: str) -> bool:
    """True when a LIVE running pane in `session` is tagged @sable_bead ==
    bead_id (dispatch evidence). Fails open (False) when the session doesn't
    exist yet. Shared by the duplicate-dispatch guard and the respawn tree-claim
    release, so both read the SAME liveness signal (SABLE-3eax)."""
    try:
        listing = _run(base + ["list-panes", "-s", "-t", session, "-F", _BEAD_FORMAT])
    except subprocess.CalledProcessError:
        listing = ""
    return bead_pane_tagged(listing, bead_id)


def main(argv: list[str] | None = None) -> int:
    p = argparse.ArgumentParser(prog="sable-spawn-worker")
    p.add_argument("bead_id")
    p.add_argument("--worktree", help="existing worktree path (else bd worktree create)")
    p.add_argument("--bundle", help="comma-separated sibling bead ids bundled with "
                                    "bead_id into the SAME worktree/branch (SABLE-q13h): "
                                    "claimed up front and rendered in full into the "
                                    "dispatch prompt, so the worker cannot skip them")
    p.add_argument("--model", help="model or 'model:reason' override")
    p.add_argument("--scope", help="short name for the worktree (else derived from bead)")
    p.add_argument("--lane", help="lane manager identity stamped on the worker "
                                  "(default: $CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME of the invoking pane)")
    p.add_argument("--session", help="target session (default: SABLE_TMUX_SESSION, "
                                     "else derived per-repo — see sable-session)")
    p.add_argument("--skip-governance", action="store_true")
    p.add_argument("--respawn", action="store_true",
                   help="REVISE / push-only close-out into an existing worktree "
                        "(SABLE-3eax): reopen a closed bead, release a stranded "
                        "stale tree-claim, and pass the duplicate guard when no "
                        "live pane carries the tag — model-check stays active. "
                        "Requires --worktree.")
    ns = p.parse_args(sys.argv[1:] if argv is None else argv)

    # --respawn re-enters a SPECIFIC existing worktree — it has no meaning without
    # one (a fresh `bd worktree create` tree has nothing to revise). Require it
    # explicitly rather than silently deriving/creating a tree.
    if ns.respawn and not ns.worktree:
        p.error("--respawn requires --worktree PATH (the existing worktree to "
                "re-enter for the REVISE / push-only close-out)")

    # --- SABLE-38zi re-dispatch guard. FIRST, before any bead fetch / tmux /
    # worktree side effect, so a refused re-dispatch from a worker pane leaves
    # nothing claimed and spawns no grandchild pane. Distinct exit 9 (throttle/
    # governance use 3-8). ---
    guard_err = worker_pane_guard()
    if guard_err:
        sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: {guard_err}\n")
        return 9

    socket = os.environ.get("SABLE_TMUX_SOCKET") or None
    base = tmux_base(socket)
    if not ns.session:
        try:
            ns.session = resolve_session(socket=socket)
        except SessionCollision as e:
            sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: {e}\n")
            return 4
    bid = ns.bead_id

    # --- dispatch throttle + host-resource guard (SABLE-mmdt). Deliberately
    # NOT behind --skip-governance (host protection, not bead hygiene) and
    # BEFORE the bead fetch/claim, so a refused spawn leaves nothing claimed. ---
    try:
        pane_listing = _run(base + ["list-panes", "-s", "-t", ns.session,
                                    "-F", _CAP_FORMAT])
    except subprocess.CalledProcessError:
        pane_listing = ""  # no session yet -> zero live workers; fail open
    cap_err = capacity_check(count_live_workers(pane_listing), worker_cap())
    if cap_err:
        sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: throttle refused — {cap_err}\n")
        return 7
    try:
        load1 = os.getloadavg()[0]
    except OSError:
        load1 = 0.0  # platform without loadavg: guard has nothing to read
    guard_err = host_guard(load1, os.cpu_count() or 1, load_threshold())
    if guard_err:
        sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: host-guard refused — {guard_err}\n")
        return 8

    # --- fetch bead for the prompt + label-based model resolution ---
    bead = parse_bead(_run(["bd", "show", bid, "--json"]))
    model, reason, model_source = resolve_model(bead_labels(bead), ns.model)
    lane = resolve_lane(ns.lane)

    # SABLE-mn1da: announce the model AND why, BEFORE any governance step that
    # can refuse — a manager must be able to see that a flat default (not a
    # ladder) picked the tier even on a spawn that never reaches the pane.
    sys.stderr.write("sable-spawn-worker: model selection — "
                     f"{model_announcement(model, reason, model_source)}\n")

    # --- SABLE-q13h: fetch bundled sibling beads (if any) for the prompt.
    # Fetched unconditionally (even under --skip-governance) since prompt
    # assembly always needs their titles/descriptions; only the up-front
    # claim below is gated on governance. ---
    bundle_ids = parse_bundle_ids(ns.bundle, bid)
    bundle_beads = [parse_bead(_run(["bd", "show", b, "--json"])) for b in bundle_ids]

    # Dispatch evidence: a LIVE running pane tagged with this bead. Computed once
    # here so the duplicate-dispatch guard AND the respawn tree-claim release
    # (SABLE-3eax) read the SAME liveness signal. Skipped only for a plain
    # --skip-governance spawn that isn't a respawn (nothing consumes it there).
    pane_ev = (_live_bead_pane(base, ns.session, bid)
               if (not ns.skip_governance or ns.respawn) else False)

    # --- governance: model-check + duplicate-dispatch + preempt + claim +
    # overlap advisory (SABLE-bldh.6 re-homed model-check/claim; SABLE-bldh.8
    # re-homes the remaining PreToolUse:Agent hooks as pre-spawn steps here).
    # The execution-mode interlock gates this whole command upstream. ---
    if not ns.skip_governance:
        err = model_check(bead_labels(bead), ns.model)
        if err:
            sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: model-check blocked — {err}\n")
            return 3

        # SABLE-d5iku: unmerged-blocker advisory. FIRST advisory in the chain,
        # ahead of the duplicate/preempt/claim steps, so the manager sees the
        # warning even when a later governance step refuses the dispatch — and
        # so it is emitted before the first bd WRITE rather than after. Covers
        # the lead bead and every --bundle sibling, since a bundle sibling can
        # be the base-premise bead just as easily as the lead. Never blocks.
        # Judged in the dispatch CWD (git reads work from any subdirectory, and
        # unlike _repo_toplevel() it cannot raise) — merge state is a property
        # of the repo being dispatched into, never of this program's location.
        dep_warning = dep_merge_advisory([bid, *bundle_ids], os.getcwd())
        if dep_warning:
            sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: {dep_warning}\n")

        # SABLE-3eax (a): a respawn (REVISE / push-only close-out) may target a
        # CLOSED bead — reopen it to in_progress FIRST, or the `bd update --claim`
        # that follows a non-respawn path traceback-crashes on it AND the worker's
        # own `bd close` has nothing to close. model-check above already ran, so
        # keeping it active is preserved.
        if ns.respawn and needs_reopen(bead):
            reopen = subprocess.run(["bd", "update", bid, "--status", "in_progress"],
                                    capture_output=True, text=True)
            if reopen.returncode != 0:
                sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: respawn could not reopen closed "
                                 f"bead {bid}: {reopen.stderr.strip()}\n")
                return 5
            bead["status"] = "in_progress"
            sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: respawn reopened closed bead {bid} "
                             "-> in_progress\n")

        # SABLE-676c: an IN_PROGRESS bead is a duplicate ONLY when dispatch
        # evidence exists — a RUNNING worker pane tagged with the bead, or the
        # derived wk-<scope> worktree already on disk. A bare claim with neither
        # is the manager claim-then-hold pattern (this bead's OWN first dispatch)
        # and must pass, not be refused as a duplicate. SABLE-3eax: a respawn
        # deliberately REUSES the worktree, so worktree-evidence is expected and
        # never blocks it — only a LIVE pane still carrying the tag does.
        tl = "" if ns.worktree else _repo_toplevel()
        wt_ev = worktree_dispatch_exists(
            prospective_worktree_path(bid, ns.scope, ns.worktree, tl))
        dup_err = already_in_progress_check(bead, pane_ev, wt_ev, respawn=ns.respawn)
        if dup_err:
            sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: duplicate-dispatch blocked — {dup_err}\n")
            return 5

        if lane:
            inbox = parse_bead_list(_run(["bd", "ready", "-l", f"for-{lane}", "--json"]))
            preempt_err = preempt_check(lane, inbox)
            if preempt_err:
                sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: preempt blocked — {preempt_err}\n")
                return 6

        if ns.respawn:
            # SABLE-3eax (c): a respawn is a REVISE / push-only close-out of work
            # THIS lane already owns — never re-run `bd update --claim`. The bead
            # is (re)opened above and already assigned; real `bd --claim` errors
            # 'already claimed' against any assignee that isn't bd's own actor
            # identity (SABLE-m40k) — which for a respawn is the norm. Ownership
            # stands from the original dispatch.
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-spawn-worker: respawn — not re-claiming {bid} "
                "(REVISE / push-only close-out of owned work)\n")
        elif bead_already_claimed_by_lane(bead, lane):
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-spawn-worker: {bid} already assigned to lane '{lane}' — "
                "skipping redundant bd update --claim (SABLE-m40k)\n")
            # SABLE-ixps: `bd update --claim` sets BOTH assignee AND status to
            # in_progress — skipping it above (correctly, to avoid the
            # already-claimed error) leaves a MANAGER-REASSIGNED bead (assignee
            # already the lane, status still OPEN) stuck OPEN while its worker
            # runs. Flip status directly, with no --claim, so it can't re-trigger
            # the assignee-already-claimed error. Only when still OPEN — a
            # self-claimed bead is already in_progress and must not be churned.
            if bead.get("status") == "open":
                status_fix = subprocess.run(
                    ["bd", "update", bid, "--status", "in_progress"],
                    capture_output=True, text=True)
                if status_fix.returncode != 0:
                    sys.stderr.write(
                        f"sable-spawn-worker: could not flip {bid} to in_progress "
                        f"after skipped claim: {status_fix.stderr.strip()}\n")
                    return 5
                bead["status"] = "in_progress"
                sys.stderr.write(
                    f"sable-spawn-worker: {bid} status open -> in_progress "
                    "(assignee already lane; SABLE-ixps)\n")
        else:
            subprocess.run(["bd", "update", bid, "--claim"], check=True)

        # SABLE-q13h: claim-all-up-front — every bundled sibling bead is
        # claimed here too, so none of them looks separately-owned to the
        # dispatched worker (see claim_bundle_beads docstring).
        if bundle_beads:
            claim_bundle_beads(bundle_beads, lane)

        in_progress = parse_bead_list(_run(["bd", "list", "--status=in_progress", "--json"]))
        overlap_verdict = overlap_check(bid, bead, in_progress)
        if overlap_verdict.decision == "deny":
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-spawn-worker: overlap-constraint blocked — {overlap_verdict.message}\n")
            return 11
        if overlap_verdict.decision == "allow":
            for partner in overlap_verdict.tagged_ids:
                tag_serialize_with(bid, partner)
                tag_serialize_with(partner, bid)
            sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: {overlap_verdict.message}\n")

    # --- worktree ---
    if ns.worktree:
        worktree = ns.worktree
        # SABLE-3eax (b): before the fresh worker runs any git, release a
        # tree-claim stranded by a reaped predecessor — tree-claim.sh would
        # otherwise DENY the respawned worker's index-mutating git ops until the
        # claim TTL-expires (the manual `sable-claim release --force` wall). Only
        # when the holder has no live pane (pane_ev False); a live pane already
        # refused the respawn in the duplicate guard above.
        if ns.respawn:
            release_msg = release_stale_tree_claim(worktree, holder_pane_live=pane_ev)
            if release_msg:
                sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: {release_msg}\n")
        # Refresh (SABLE-bldh.8), lowest priority: only reusing an EXISTING
        # worktree needs a rebase — a freshly `bd worktree create`d tree below
        # is already at the base HEAD.
        if not ns.skip_governance:
            # Pass the raw SABLE_BASE_BRANCH (None when unset) — refresh_worktree
            # resolves the per-repo integration base itself (SABLE-ybdm); an
            # explicit env value still wins inside resolve_refresh_base.
            refresh_warning = refresh_worktree(
                worktree, os.environ.get("SABLE_BASE_BRANCH"))
            if refresh_warning:
                sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: {refresh_warning}\n")
    else:
        wt_name = worktree_name(bid, ns.scope)
        toplevel = _run(["git", "rev-parse", "--show-toplevel"]).strip()
        # Compute the path ONCE and use it for BOTH the bd-create target and the
        # tmux -c target — computing them separately dropped the worker in $HOME
        # (SABLE-bldh.11). Pass --branch explicitly so the absolute path is not
        # also taken as the branch name.
        worktree = resolve_worktree_path(toplevel, wt_name)
        _run(["bd", "worktree", "create", worktree, "--branch", wt_name])
    branch = Path(worktree).name

    # SABLE-i5739: tag every bead landing in this worktree (the lead bead PLUS
    # any --bundle siblings — they share this SAME branch, see the --bundle
    # help text above) with the branch as structured metadata, so the
    # reconciliation floor can resolve branch->bead without a prose search.
    # Gated on governance like every other bd WRITE in this module (claim,
    # overlap serialize_with tagging above) — a --skip-governance dispatch is
    # a stand-in/test spawn against a bead this caller does not own writing
    # to, and must leave it untouched exactly as the claim/status writes do.
    if not ns.skip_governance:
        for tag_id in [bid, *bundle_ids]:
            tag_branch_metadata(tag_id, branch)

    # SABLE-ji4h: link opted-in gitignored fixtures into the worktree. Placed
    # AFTER both arms above so a --respawn into an existing tree is repaired
    # too, not just a freshly created one. Idempotent (skip-exists) and silent
    # for repos that have not opted in.
    for rel, action, _src, dst in link_fixture_paths(
            _run(["git", "rev-parse", "--show-toplevel"]).strip(), worktree):
        if action == "link":
            sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: linked fixtures {rel} -> {dst}\n")
        elif action.startswith("link-failed") or action == "skip-escapes-repo":
            sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: fixture {rel}: {action}\n")

    # --- write the dispatch prompt file (keeps the worktree clean) ---
    ddir = dispatch_dir()
    ddir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    dispatch_path = ddir / f"{bid}.md"
    bundle_arg = [{"id": b.get("id", i), "title": b.get("title", ""),
                  "description": b.get("description", "")}
                 for i, b in zip(bundle_ids, bundle_beads)]
    dispatch_path.write_text(assemble_dispatch_prompt(
        bid, bead.get("title", ""), bead.get("description", ""),
        worktree, branch, model, bundle=bundle_arg))

    # --- open the worker window (stamped with the lane identity) + capture pane ---
    # SABLE-5v9n: set remain-on-exit GLOBALLY, BEFORE the window is created,
    # so it is already in effect the instant the pane's process starts. A
    # very fast-exiting command (or a claude boot that dies immediately) can
    # exit before any POST-creation per-pane `set-option` call would land —
    # setting it after new-window races the pane's own destruction and every
    # subsequent tag-set call fails with "no such pane". A global default set
    # first has no such window: every pane on this server inherits it from
    # creation.
    subprocess.run(base + ["set-option", "-g", "remain-on-exit", "on"], check=True)
    win = window_name(bid)
    wcmd = with_lifecycle_flags(worker_command(model, os.environ.get("SABLE_WORKER_CMD")))
    pane_id = _run(base + new_window_args(ns.session, win, worktree,
                                          worker_env_args(lane), wcmd)).strip()

    # --- tag the pane for the registry + reaper. @sable_status is NOT set
    # here (SABLE-5v9n): with_lifecycle_flags already sets it running/done
    # from INSIDE the pane's own script — a manager-side write here would
    # race a fast-exiting worker and could clobber a done flip that already
    # landed. @sable_role/@sable_bead/@sable_repo/@sable_lane have no such
    # writer on the pane side, so setting them post-creation is race-free. See
    # worker_pane_tags for the per-tag rationale (incl. the SABLE-dcw2 lane). ---
    for key, val in worker_pane_tags(bid, repo_root(), lane):
        subprocess.run(base + ["set-option", "-p", "-t", pane_id, key, val], check=True)

    # --- deliver the read-instruction, beating the boot + dropped-Enter race
    #     (SABLE-91m3): wait for the TUI to be ready, then submit with retries. ---
    ready_timeout = float(os.environ.get("SABLE_DISPATCH_READY_TIMEOUT", "25"))
    submit_tries = int(os.environ.get("SABLE_DISPATCH_SUBMIT_TRIES", "8"))
    poll_interval = float(os.environ.get("SABLE_DISPATCH_POLL_INTERVAL", "1.0"))
    if ready_timeout > 0:
        # SABLE-m94k: the boolean return was previously DISCARDED here, so a
        # pane stuck on an unrecognized dialog/selector (accept_startup_gate
        # only clears the two KNOWN startup gates) fell through to
        # deliver_dispatch unconditionally — typing the dispatch text INTO
        # the dialog while the worker sat idle, indistinguishable from a
        # working lane until a manual capture-pane. Refuse to type instead:
        # fail LOUD (nonzero exit naming the pane), leave the bead claim
        # intact for the dispatching manager to retry.
        if not wait_for_ready(base, pane_id, ready_timeout, interval=poll_interval):
            cap = capture_pane(base, pane_id)
            posture = ("an interactive dialog/selector" if dialog_posture(cap)
                       else "not in composer posture (still booting or stuck)")
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-spawn-worker: REFUSING to type into {pane_id} for {bid} — "
                f"pane shows {posture}, not the composer. Dispatch prompt was NOT "
                f"typed; {bid} is left claimed for retry. Investigate with "
                f"`tmux capture-pane -p -t {pane_id}` and re-spawn once clear.\n")
            return 10
    delivered = deliver_dispatch(base, pane_id, read_instruction(str(dispatch_path)),
                                 bid, tries=submit_tries, interval=poll_interval)
    if not delivered:
        sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: WARNING dispatch may be unsubmitted in "
                         f"{pane_id}; nudge with: tmux send-keys -t {pane_id} Enter\n")

    # --- SABLE-qw9jv: stamp the model provenance onto the bead(s). LAST, after
    # the pane exists and the dispatch has been typed into it, so the stamp is
    # a record of a spawn that actually happened — every refusal path above
    # returns before this point and leaves no attribution behind. Value comes
    # from the command that LAUNCHED (launched_model), never from ns.model.
    # Bundled siblings share this pane, hence this model. Gated on governance
    # like every other bd WRITE here: a --skip-governance stand-in spawn must
    # leave a bead it does not own untouched. ---
    ran = launched_model(wcmd)
    stamped_model = ran or "unknown"
    stamped_source = model_source if ran else "worker-cmd-override"
    if ran and ran != model:
        sys.stderr.write(
            f"sable-spawn-worker: NOTE launched model '{ran}' differs from the "
            f"resolved model '{model}' (SABLE_WORKER_CMD override) — recording "
            "what launched\n")
    elif not ran:
        sys.stderr.write(
            "sable-spawn-worker: NOTE worker command names no --model "
            f"({wcmd!r}) — recording model=unknown rather than asserting "
            f"'{model}' ran\n")
    if not ns.skip_governance:
        for tag_id in [bid, *bundle_ids]:
            tag_model_metadata(tag_id, stamped_model, stamped_source)

    note = (f" ({model_announcement(model, reason, model_source)}"
            + (f", lane {lane}" if lane else "") + ")")
    sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: spawned {win} for {bid} at {pane_id}{note}\n")
    sys.stderr.write(f"sable-spawn-worker: model provenance for {bid}"
                     + (f" (+{','.join(bundle_ids)})" if bundle_ids else "")
                     + f": model={stamped_model} model_source={stamped_source}"
                     + (" [not stamped: --skip-governance]" if ns.skip_governance else "")
                     + "\n")
    return 0


if __name__ == "__main__":
    sys.exit(main())
